\section{Vote-Sellers and Vote-Buyers: Two Sides of the Same Coin?}

% general hook on advanced democracies, and the decline on clientelism// US Context.
Many advanced democracies were first very clientelistic political systems. For instance, \citet[200]{Stokes:2013cj} explains that in the nineteenth-century United States ``vote buying was commonplace.'' In Chicago, New York City, Newark, and other big cities, votes were exchanged for ``cash, food, alcohol, health care, poverty relief, and myriad other benefits,''\footnote{\citet[200]{Stokes:2013cj}.} even resembling the worst practices in the current developing world. The street price of the right to vote freely seemed to be very low. Bensel explains that ``[voters] handed in a party ticket in return for a shot of whiskey, a pair of boots, or a small amount of money.''\footnote{In \citet[227]{Stokes:2013cj}.} Vote buying, besides being cheap, it was ``the major urban political institution in the late nineteenth century''\footnote{\citet[2]{Erie:1990aa}.} in ``one-half of the nation's twenty largest cities''\footnote{\citet[2]{Erie:1990aa}.} in the United States. Other students of American political development have analyzed vote-buying in more detail, confirming both its early and generalized occurrence.\footnote{See particularly \citet{Bensel:2004aa} and \citet{Campbell:2005aa}.} However, nowadays vote-buying seemed to have declined considerably.  For instance, \citet[201]{Stokes:2013cj} has shown that industrialization has driven up the median income of the electorate, making vote-buying a more expensive strategy for party machines.\footnote{However, see \citet[320]{Kitschelt2007}, who explain that ``it is not economic development that accounts for the emergence and decline of varying linkage practices and not even the nature of formal democratic institutions,'' but higher levels of ``[s]tate involvement in the public sector.''} In line with that, \autoref{fig:lapop:bar:chart:plot} suggests---using survey data---that $\Sexpr{round(as.numeric(as.numeric(table(clientelism)["Never"]) * 100) / lapop.bar.chart.N, 1)}$\% of respondents have \emph{never} received a clientelistic offer from a political party.\footnote{A very small percentage ($\Sexpr{round(as.numeric(as.numeric(table(clientelism)["Often"]) + as.numeric(table(clientelism)["Sometimes"]) * 100 ) / lapop.bar.chart.N, 1)}$\%) reports to have received some kind of clientelistic offer from a political party.}


% Hook
We seem to know that vote-\emph{buyers} cannot afford this strategy any longer, not at least in a massive scale, thus making vote-buying a rare event. However, several questions remain unanswered. Most of them pertain to vote-\emph{sellers}. \emph{Has the decline in vote-buying in the United States been paired with improvements in voters' democratic values? What would voters do, if offered the chance to sell their votes? Would they sell their votes (and what price), or would they consciously opt-out of vote-selling because they oppose vote-selling?} Given the emphasis so far has been on vote-\emph{buying}, prior studies do not offer answers to these questions.\footnote{\citet{Hicken2014,Hicken2015} constitute two very important exceptions.} That is, often times studies usually focus on whether \emph{parties} have attempted to buy votes, overlooking whether voters have attempted to \emph{sell} their votes. For instance, \autoref{fig:lapop:bar:chart:plot} shows responses to whether \emph{a candidate or someone from a political party} has offered something in exchange for people's votes. I contend that this \emph{demand-side bias} gives an incomplete picture. For one, it might give the falsely optimistic impression that U.S. voters have \emph{healthier} democratic values, ``thus'' engaging almost \emph{never} in clientelism. Moreover, demand-side studies of clientelism have traditionally studied, except for a number of exceptions,\footnote{Notably, \citet{Zarazaga2015a} interviewed 120 brokers in Argentina.} \emph{what parties do} by asking \emph{voters} about what \emph{parties} do. This \emph{reverse demand-side bias} might cause other problems too. For instance, not only asking directly survey respondents about illegal behaviors constitutes an important source of social desirability bias.\footnote{\citet{Gonzalez-Ocantos2012}. Unfortunately, their focus is on vote-\emph{buying}, overlooking vote-\emph{selling}. They ask whether ``candidates or activists gave [voters] a gift or did a favor.''} Also, \emph{indirect learning} (i.e., learning about what parties do by asking voters) is inevitable confounded with the respondent's frustrations and/or positive opinions about political parties, and politics in general. Ultimately, this paper is an attempt to bridge the gap between vote-\emph{sellers} and vote-\emph{buyers}, by concentrating where the supply meets the demand, not by criticizing the vote-\emph{buying} literature. Particularly, the paper advances our knowledge about the determinants of vote-\emph{selling} by exploiting variation from a list and conjoint experiments, from which I am able to predict individual likelihoods of vote-selling, price elasticity on the willingness to sell, and its connection with democratic support. It is worth noting that the author is not aware of any other study where voters in an advanced democracy are asked (via an experimental design) whether they would sell their votes. 



