% summarize the paper, explain main findings.
I collected a novel dataset representative at the national level, where a total of $\Sexpr{total.sample.size}$ U.S. voters participated between March 2nd and March 6th in 2016 in both a list experiment and a conjoint experiment. Leveraging these two experimental designs, I was able to identify the conditions under which U.S. voters were more likely to sell their votes, at what price, whether they would systematically lie about it, and which democratic values should fail to make voters likely vote-sellers. Next, I paired those individual predictions with a battery of experimental questions which were embedded into a conjoint experiment. This portion of the study was designed to learn about the micro dynamics of democratic support, particularly paying attention to the multi-dimensional aspects of ``support for democracy.'' Building on the literature about the quantitative measurement of democracy support,\footnote{\citet{Carlin2006,Carlin2011a,Carlin2017}, \citet{KiewietdeJonge2016} and \citet{Linde2003}.} I designed a conjoint experiment to capture which democratic dimension should fail to predict likely vote-sellers. Leveraging the theoretical typology of what constitutes a democracy, famously established in \citet{Dahl:1971uw}, and expanded by \citet{ODonnell2001},\footnote{See particularly \citet{Luna2006}.} I was able to disentangle which portion of ``democratic support'' should fall to predict individual vote-selling. I find that U.S. voters are very much willing to sell their votes, they would sell it at an optimal price of \$$\Sexpr{round(line_intersection$x,0)}$, and that they systematically lie about it. These findings are striking, going against the standard optimistic panorama offered by analysts of the vote-\emph{buying} approach, reflecting a possible democratic crisis among the electorate. Democrats, liberals, and lower-income individuals are systematically more likely to sell than the rest, while education does not have a systematic impact. As of the conjoint portion, out of the three democratic dimensions, e.g. democratic, liberal, and republican components, I find that the first one is systematically associated with vote-selling in different and interesting ways. While individuals who think that that ``citizens can \emph{run} for elections'' increases the chances of vote-selling, individuals who think that ``citizens can \emph{vote}'' decreases vote-selling. I advance a working hypothesis where I explain that \todo{?}


 



